      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Local SEO link building</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local link building</strong> is the practice of earning backlinks from websites with geographic relevance to your business — local news outlets, chambers of commerce, community organizations, and area businesses. Unlike standard link building that targets domain authority alone, local link building adds a geographic dimension that tells Google your business is genuinely embedded in its community.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">#1 for local organic</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Sustainable pace</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2-3 links per month</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local businesses do citations and call it link building. Citations matter, but they're table stakes. The businesses pulling away from competitors are investing in the harder, higher-value work: editorial links from locally relevant websites that Google uses as community trust signals.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is local link building?</h2>
        <p>Local link building is a subset of link building focused on geographic relevance. Where standard SEO link building pursues domain authority from any high-quality website, local link building specifically targets websites tied to your business's geography.</p>
        <p>The distinction matters because Google's local algorithm weighs geographic relevance separately from raw link authority. A link from a local newspaper, a city chamber of commerce, or a community nonprofit signals that your business is embedded in its local community — a trust signal that a generic high-DA blog link from across the country does not provide.</p>
        <p>Moz's Local Search Ranking Factors study identifies link signals as the <strong>#1 factor for local organic rankings</strong> and the #2 factor for local pack rankings. Local businesses that consistently build locally relevant links outrank competitors who rely on citations alone.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Moz research</div>
          <p>Moz's annual Local Search Ranking Factors study places link signals at the top of local organic rankings. The research specifically notes that <strong>links from locally relevant sources carry extra geographic authority</strong> beyond their raw domain authority — .gov, .edu, and local news links perform disproportionately well in local search.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local link building matters</h2>
        <p>Three reasons local link building produces compounding returns that most other local SEO tactics don't:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Local pack ranking signal.</strong> While your Google Business Profile drives most local pack signals, the prominence factor — which includes your website's backlink profile — accounts for roughly 11% of local pack rankings. Local links build this prominence more efficiently than generic links.</li>
          <li><strong>Geographic relevance signal.</strong> Links from .gov pages, local newspapers, and community organizations tell Google that your business is genuinely part of its location's ecosystem. This geographic authority does not accumulate through paid ads or directory submissions.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding authority.</strong> Each local link you earn reduces the effort required for the next one. A business known in the community as a sponsor, expert source, or active participant earns links more naturally over time. The first 10 are the hardest.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How local link building works — core tactics</h2>

        <h3>Community-based tactics</h3>
        <p>These produce the highest-quality local links with strong geographic signals:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sponsor local events and teams.</strong> A $300-500 sponsorship of a local charity run, Little League team, or school event typically earns a sponsor page link from the organization's website. These are high-trust, .org links with clear local relevance.</li>
          <li><strong>Chamber of commerce membership.</strong> Most chambers list members on their website with a link. Join your local chamber and any industry-specific local business associations in your area.</li>
          <li><strong>Business partnerships and cross-promotion.</strong> Complementary businesses (a plumber and an HVAC company, a dentist and an orthodontist) can link to each other on "trusted partners" pages. Keep it relevant and avoid reciprocal link schemes at scale.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Content-driven tactics</h3>
        <p>Create content so locally useful that area publications reference it:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Local data studies.</strong> "Most common roof problems in [City] by neighborhood" — original research that local media can link to when covering local real estate, weather, or home services stories.</li>
          <li><strong>Neighborhood guides and local event roundups.</strong> Content that local blogs, community newsletters, and news sites naturally reference when covering local life.</li>
          <li><strong>Local statistics and surveys.</strong> Commission or conduct surveys about local business issues, consumer trends, or community topics. The data attracts links from local media.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>PR and media tactics</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Build journalist relationships.</strong> Find the reporters who cover your industry at local newspapers and TV news stations. Offer yourself as an expert source for local angles. A mention with a link is worth more than most directory submissions.</li>
          <li><strong>Press releases for genuine business news.</strong> Grand openings, expansions, community initiatives, and awards are legitimate press release subjects that local outlets will cover with a link.</li>
          <li><strong>HARO (Help a Reporter Out) filtered by local.</strong> Filter HARO requests to your metro area and respond to journalist queries with specific, expert answers.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Local link sources ranked by value</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Source type</th><th>Geographic signal</th><th>Typical DA</th><th>Difficulty to earn</th></tr>
            </thead>
